7. LINUX ORCHESTRATION ARCHITECTURE

(From the Linux orchestration document)

7.1 Stack Overview

Layer Tools
Provisioning Terraform, Ansible
Container Orchestration Kubernetes (core), K3s (edge), KubeEdge
GitOps ArgoCD, Flux
Service Mesh Istio, Cilium
Observability Prometheus, Grafana, Loki, Tempo
Security Vault, Falco, OPA/Gatekeeper
Storage Rook/Ceph (core), Longhorn (edge)

7.2 Key Features

· Immutable infrastructure with CoreOS Flatcar
· Edge autonomy via K3s and local control loops
· GitOps for declarative management of all clusters
· eBPF networking with Cilium for high performance and security
· Hardened nodes with CIS benchmarks, SELinux, and Falco runtime security

---

8. AUTONOMOUS CAMPUS CONTROL SOFTWARE ARCHITECTURE

(From the control software document)

8.1 High‑Level Components

· Cognitive Core Interface – global aggregation and command distribution
· Zone Controllers – local state management, decision making, actuation
· Global Decision Engine – campus‑wide optimization (quantum‑inspired)
· Digital Twin Integration – simulation and what‑if analysis
· Sensor Fusion – edge and core multi‑modal data integration
· Actuation Manager – device‑specific command translation
· Safety Monitor – continuous safety envelope enforcement
· HITL Console – human oversight and override

8.2 Control Loops

Timescale Examples Location
ms‑s Robot obstacle avoidance, emergency response Edge
s‑min HVAC adjustment, robot task coordination Edge
min‑h Energy optimization, shuttle routing Core
day‑month Model retraining, policy refinement Core

8.3 Human‑in‑the‑Loop Tiers

· Tier 1: Fully autonomous (low risk)
· Tier 2: Human‑on‑the‑loop (can veto)
· Tier 3: Human‑in‑the‑loop (explicit approval)
· Tier 4: Manual only (hardware interlocks)

